            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "It's possible that this could be simplified, sure. I sort of just hacked at it until it behaved properly, and there were a few other edge cases that were brought up at the time.\n\nThe intention is that if a `deno.lock` or `deno.json` file is found closer than other root markers (or at the same level), then it's a deno file. If there's a deno.lock file that's further away than other root markers, then it might not be.\n\nFor example, you might have something like this in a complicated monorepo:\n\n```\n./.git/\n./deno.lock\n./deno.json\n./src/foo.ts   <-- deno file\n./npmproject/ <-- nested non-deno project\n./npmproject/package-lock.json\n./npmproject/package.json\n./npmproject/src/foo.ts  <-- not a deno file\n./npmproject/packages/denoproject/ <-- sub-workspace in the non-deno project\n./npmproject/packages/denoproject/deno.json\n./npmproject/packages/denoproject/src/foo.ts <-- this is a deno file\n```\n\nI ran into this on the getsentry/sentry-javascript project, which is _mostly_ traditional typescript that should be handled by `ts_ls`, but has a deno SDK in `packages/deno` which is code that runs on Deno.",
