        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Interesting example. From reading the code I don't think the current config works that way.\nThe only non-deno root marker is `.git`. So the result of `root_dir` will be the same for `./src/foo.ts` and `./npmproject/src/foo.ts`. Both will be marked as deno files, because `deno_root` and `project_root` are the same.\n\nSo we should check for `package.json`, `package-lock.json` and the likes.\nA similar thing happens in the vtsls and eslint configs. So wouldn't it make sense to have shared logic?\nThen at least the various lsps would be attached consistently.\nThe shared function could determine what the current project type is (npm, deno, bun) by looking at the closest root marker.\nIt would have to apply a (configurable?) preference for the situation where there are multiple different markers in the same root directory.\nEverywhere we need to distinguish this we could then just call this project type function and e.g. activate the ls in `denols.lua` or skip activation in `vtsls.lua` and `eslint.lua` if the project is a deno project.\nI guess if there is no difference for bun projects, the function could simply be `is_deno_project`:\n\n```lua\nlocal prefer_deno = false\nfunction is_deno_project()\n  local deno_root = vim.fs.root(bufnr, { 'deno.json', 'deno.jsonc', 'deno.lock' })\n  if not deno_root then\n    return false\n  end\n\n  local other_root = vim.fs.root(bufnr, { 'package-lock.json', 'yarn.lock', 'pnpm-lock.yaml', 'bun.lockb', 'bun.lock' })\n  return not other_root or #deno_root > #other_root or deno_root == other_root and prefer_deno \nend\n```\n\nCurrently there is a distinction between deno project root and deno lock root in the code (which does not have any effect, because both are always also the project_root atm). So maybe that should be taken into account for deciding when we have both a deno root marker and another root marker in the same directory, but I don't know what the reasoning there might be.\n",
